    "content": "- URL shorteners transform long URLs into short, manageable links.\n- High-volume services handle millions of new URLs daily and billions over time.\n- Storage requirements for billions of URLs are substantial (e.g., 36TB for 365 billion URLs).\n- Short URL generation requires unique identifiers, often 7 characters long for sufficient combinations (62^7 > 3.5 trillion).\n- Two primary URL generation approaches: hashing and sequential ID generation (base 62 conversion).\n- Hashing approach risks collisions, requiring re-tries and database lookups.\n- Sequential ID generation (base 62) is elegant, collision-free, and math-based, but has challenges with distributed ID generation and security (predictability).\n- URL redirection requires fast lookups: cache first, then database.\n- 301 status codes are used for permanent redirects, enabling browser caching.\n- Scaling lookup performance necessitates database replication and sharding for high traffic.\n- URL shorteners are prime examples of distributed systems challenges: ID generation, caching, database scaling, sharding, rate limiting, analytics, and security.\n- The underlying engineering patterns (ID generation, caching, sharding) are prevalent in many large-scale applications (e.g., Twitter, Slack, Instagram, Netflix, Uber)."
